On 1/4/17 at the R&L Carriers terminal in Kansas City, MO, a 55 gallon steel drum of UN1170 Ethanol was punctured by a fork lift blade while unloading a trailer.  The damaged drum released approximately 25 gallons of material to the trailer floor and approximately 5 to the concrete parking area.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release.  All free product was recovered with the use of granular absorbents.  The impacted absorbents were containerized into a 55 gallon steel drum.  The damaged drum of material was overpacked into an 85 gallon steel drum.  Both the over pack and drum of impacted absorbents were staged on site pending profiling and proper disposal.

It was reported that due to a nail puncture, 1-3 gallon poly pail was impacted releasing 2 gallons of UN3109 to the trailer floor and approx. 1/3 of the 2 gallons reached the Rayloc asphalt parking lot. Contractor over-packed the impacted poly pail and the spent absorbents. The impacted areas were neutralized with soda ash. All generated waste was taken off site.

column168: During a routine load check within the first hour after pickup, a driver noticed a small amount of liquid leaking from the rear gauge. column168: At 1655 on 01/12/2017 ERTS was contacted by Cole Williamson from XPO XKC. It was reported that the trailer was loaded for delivery and the driver noticed that there was material leaking from the trailer. The terminal personnel backed the trailer to the dock door and began unloading the freight. They found two 1 gallon pails of UN 1263 that had apparently been hit by a forklift.  The caller reported that the release had impacted the trailer floor, the apron and the loading dock. The caller stated that if they were allowed to clean the release, they would. The SDS was forwarded to the caller for their reference. The caller said that they would clean the release with granular absorbents and then place all used absorbents and impacted pails into a 55 gallon steel drum, label as non hazardous then place into OS&D. It was reported that the driver of a Trimac MC307 Cargo Tanker carrying UN3265 N-Heptanoic Acid pulled into the Travel Centers of America truck stop in Seville, OH and noticed the product leaking from the seam in the skid of the tanker. Hoses and pumps were disconnected and the tanker was decontaminated. (1) 55 gallon poly drum of non hazardous waste was generated and taken offsite for disposal. There were no drains, soils, or waterways impacted by this incident.

(METHYL ISOBUTYL CARBINOL    PHOSPHORIC ACID ESTERS AMINE SALT). The tank car was isolated and the shipper,  The Lubrizol Corp , was notified via Chemtrec, report #2017-0113-00136 . Environmental Management Specialists (EMS), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Avon Terminal. EMS found that two of the six manway securement bolts were less than tool tight. The shipper representative, Joe, Eskra, 216-447-6374 was notified of the situation found. The tank car was properly secured and released back into transportation. The environmental contractor determined that the release was due to a faulty pressure release valve.  The contractor attempted to secure the valve but were unable to stop the release.  The cylinder was removed from the terminal and allowed to off gas under controlled conditions.  The contractors supervised the tank until it was completely empty.  The empty tank was then staged at terminal for XPO personnel to manage.

column168: On 1/10/2017, a Schneider Bulk DOT 407 trailer, trailer number 28252, was involved in a multiple vehicle accident along I-20 west bound near mile marker 89 in Vance, Alabama.  The trailer was carrying 45,420 pounds of UN3082 Calsoft T-60.  The trailer was side swiped and rear ended by a passenger vehicle while in transit.  The tank body was dented along its passenger side near its middle and the rear bulk head was dented as well. There was no damage to any valves or outlet lines on the tanker and there was no release of any product.  The tractor and tanker were towed to a nearby wrecker service yard in order to transfer the product to  a relief tanker.  On 1/12/17, an environmental contractor was dispatched to perform the product transfer. The material was transferred into a DOT 407 relief tanker without incident.  The damaged tanker was then taken for repairs, testing and re-certification.

When our truck was being unloaded at our facility in Linden, NJ, a small amount of liquid was discovered on the floor of the truck. Upon closer inspection by facility personnel wearing appropriate PPE, it was found that a drum was leaking from its lid gasket. The quantity of the leak was 8 ounces, all of which was released to the floor of the truck and side of the drum; none to soil, ground, or water. Further inspection revealed the drum ring, locking nut, and bungs to be properly tightened and torqued. The gasket was found to be misaligned in the drum ring. The drum head was replaced with another of correct type head, ring, and gasket. Facility personnel wearing appropriate PPE fully remediated the spill using absorbents and spills pads; the waste generated from the cleanup was placed in the appropriate branch waste stream container.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. However, the driver was instructed to: 1) conduct a  thorough inspection of each container before acceptance 2) if any evidence of a reduction in structural integrity or improper closure is found to take appropriate action to either fix the closure issues or place the container into a suitable salvage drum or re-containerize before transportation is initiated. In addition, the shipper was advised of the incident and was requested to follow the manufacturers printed closure instructions carefully when closing drums, and to inspect all drums in current inventory for any containers with suspect closure or integrity issues.

column168: LANGER TRANSPORT HAD A LOADED TRAILER OF METHANOL STORED IN OUR YARD OVER THE WEEKEND THAT WAS SCHEDULED TO GO OUT FOR DELIVERY ON MONDAY JANUARY 9TH. ON THE MORNING OF JANUARY 9TH, THE DRIVER THAT WAS SCHEDULED TO DELIVER THE LOAD HOOKED UP TO THE TRAILER AND PROCEEDED OUT OF THE LANGER YARD. AS HE WAS SCHEDULED TO DELIVER THE LOAD HOOKED UP TO THE TRAILER AND PROCEEDED OUT OF THE LANGER YARD. AS HE WAS GETTING ONTO THE HIGHWAY THE TRAILER DISCONNECTED FORM THE TRACTOR AND FELL ON IT LANDING GEAR. THE WEIGHT OF THE TRAILER CAUSED THE LANDING GEAR TO COLLAPSE AND A BOLT THAT WAS PART OF THE LANDING GEAR PUNCTURED THE BARREL OF THE TRAILER. THE BOLT CAUSED A SMALL PUNCTURE BUT DID NOT GO ALL THE WAY THROUGH THE BARREL OF THE TRAILER.     THE DRIVE GOT OUT OF HIS TRACTOR, ASSESSED THE SITUATION AND DISCOVERED THAT THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT DRIPPING OUT OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY TOOK OUT HIS SPILL KIT AND PUT ABSORBENT PADS AND PLACED A BUCKET UNDERNEATH THE DRIP. HE THEN WENT BACK TO THE OFFICE AND REPORTED WHAT HAPPENED AND WE CALLED THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES.     SINCE THE INCIDENT HAPPENED DIRECTLY IN FROM OF LANGER TRANSPORT WE WERE ABLE TO REACT FAST AND HAD OUT IN HOUSE RESPONDENTS PLUG UP THE HOLE AND SPREAD SPEEDY DRY ON THE SPORTS WHERE THE PRODUCT HIT THE GROUND. WHILE THE LEAK WAS BEING CONTAINED WE TRANSLOADED THE SHIPMENT INTO ANOTHER TRAILER. WHEN THE PROCESS WAS COMPLETE THE DAMAGE TRAILER WAS TOWED BACK INTO THE LANGER YARD.
column169: THE INITIAL INCIDENT OF THE TRAILER SEPARATING FORM THE TRACTOR OCCURRED DUE TO DRIVER ERROR. THE DRIVER FAILED TO VISUALLY INSPECT HIS FIFTH WHEEL AND ENSURE THAT THE JAWS OF THE FIFTH WHEEL WERE WRAPPED AROUND THE KINGPIN OF THE TRAILER. THIS IS A MAJOR VIOLATION OF COMPANY POLICY THAT IS COVERED DURING THE TRAINING PROCESS. WE WILL CONTINUE TO EMPHASIZE THIS PROCEDURE AND THE IMPORTANCE OF IT.     IN REGARDS TO THE TRAILER LEAKING THE DRIVER DID EVERYTHING HE WAS TRAINED TO DO. HE IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE LEAK BY USING HIS SPILL KIT THAT WAS SUPPLIED TO HIM.     AS A LEARNING TOOL WE WILL INFORM ALL OUR DRIVERS ABOUT THIS INCIDENT AND STRESS THE IMPORTANCE OF FOLLOWING THE COMPANY WHEN HOOKING UP TO A TRAILER. THIS WILL BE DONE WITH A MEMO ABOUT THE EVENT BEING PLACED INTO THEIR PAYCHECKS AND DISCUSSED AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS NORTHBOUND ON RIGHTEOUS RIDGE ROAD AROUND 9:30AM EST ON JAN 16, 2017 WHEN HE DROVE OFF THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY ONTO THE SOFT SHOULDER. IN AN EFFORT TO RETURN TO THE HIGHWAY HE LOST CONTROL AND ROLLED THE TRUCK ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE. RICKY SAYS HE WAS TRAVELING APPROXIMATELY 40-45 MPH. THE SPEED LIMIT IS POSTED AT 40 MPH. HE WAS UNABLE TO EXPLAIN WHY HE DROVE OFF THE ROAD.     THE TRUCK ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE, SOME CYLINDERS WERE THROWN ONTO THE ROAD, ONE 336 CUBIT FEET OF 72/25/ARGON/CO2 MIX RELIEVED, AND 1 CRADLE THAT CONTAINED 12 CYLINDERS X 300 CUBIC FEET= 3600 OF COMPRESSED OXYGEN.     THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE IS HARD TO DETERMINE, IT WOULD HAVE BEEN A SHORT TIME TO RELIEVE CONTENTS.
column169: THESE CYLINDERS ARE DESIGNED TO HAVE CAPS AND THE CRADLES ARE BUILT TO WITHSTAND NORMAL SHIPPING AND HANDLING OPERATIONS. THIS WAS AN UNUSUAL EVENT TO HAVE THESE CONTAINERS SPILLED ONTO A PAVED HIGHWAY.     THE DRIVER WILL HAVE A REVIEW, POST ACCIDENT RIDE ALONG WITH OUR REGIONAL DRIVER TRAINER BEFORE GETTING BACK ON THE ROAD.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED LEAKING AT THE DHL SERVICE CENTER (LGB) LOCATED AT 1111 E. WATSON CENTER ROAD SUITE B CARSON, CALIFORNIA 90745, AT 18:53 PST ON JANUARY 17TH. THE DHL PERSONNEL TOOK SWIFT ACTION, RETRIEVED THE SHIPMENT AND PLACED IT INTO A PLASTIC LETTER TOTE WITH ABSORBENT PADS. UPON INVESTIGATION BY HAZ MAT SPILL RESPONDENTS, IT WAS FOUND THE OUTER PACKAGING OF THE SHIPMENT WAS STAMPED AS GROUND LIMITED QUANTITY. INSIDE THE BOX WAS A 1 GALLON METAL CAN OF PAINT, LOADED ON ITS SIDE, AGAINST ORIENTATION. THE CAN HAD NO ADDITIONAL MEANS OF CLOSURE. IT WAS A SIMPLE SNAP- ON LID. THE INVOICE WITH THE PACKAGE DESCRIBED THE CONTENTS AS "PAINT FOR CARS". THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT PROPERLY PREPARED FOR INTERNATIONAL AIR TRANSPORT AND WAS NOT ACCOMPANIED BY A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION OF DANGEROUS GOODS. THE SHIPMENT WAS TRANSPORTED VIA GROUND (TUCK) FROM SHIPPER'S LOCATION TO THE DHL SERVICE CENTER, WHERE THE LEAK OCCURRED.

column168: BNSF 880216 was noted as dripping liquid from the flange between the BOV and the nozzle. Onsite BNSF mechanical responder tightened the Top-operated BOV handle about 1/8-1/4 turn and was able to stop leak. Contractor, NRC, arrived onsite and found the flange bolts were all loose, causing the valve to not seal properly. The flange bolts were all tool-tightened and the BOV was monitored for any further leakage. NRC estimates about 20 gallons leaked onto the ballast. NRC did not notice any further release from the car. An OTMA was requested and granted to move car to home shop for repairs.

This release has impacted a portion of the dock floor. No soils, drains, or waterways have been impacted. The release duration was immediate. A certified environmental service contractor conducted cleanup operations for this release. The waste generated will be disposed of in accordance with regulations.

On January 27, 2017,  R & L Carriers (FON Terminal) notified ERTS in regards to a hazardous, UN1760, Dibutlytin/Dilaurate, 8, III (PRO#926232732) release. According to the caller, terminal personnel were unloading a trailer (LE0498) from the shipper, when terminal personnel punctured 1-55 gallon steel drum of product with a forklift. Approximately 20 gallons of  product has been released to the trailer floor. Contractor indicated that the drum only appears to have lost approximately 10 gallons. Contractor indicated that approximately 0.5 gallon of product was released to the asphalt underneath the trailer. Contractor will use soda ash to neutralize the release. Contractor has identified the the product as UN1760, Dabco T-12 Catalyst, 8, III. Contractor generated 1-2-95 gallon poly drum that contains the damaged drum, product and cleanup debris.

column168: On 1/31/2017, a 5 gallon poly pail of UN1263 2k antifog coating paint part A arrived punctured and leaking in a trailer at the XPO Logistics facility in Laredo, TX. The pail had been punctured by a nail on the pallet on which it was loaded. The damaged pail released approximately 1 pint of material in the trailer and on the dock floor.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to clean the release.  The release was cleaned with absorbent pads. The impacted pads and damaged pail were overpacked into a 55 gallon poly drum and labeled as salvage with all applicable DOT labeling.  The over pack drum was staged onsite for XPO personnel to manage.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: When getting ready to leave, delivery driver noticed something leaking in his trailer. Further investigation revealed that a drum in his trailer was leaking from a drum that had been staged on a pallet with a nail protruding from it. Drum was removed from trailer and spilled material neutralized and cleaned up with absorbent material.
column169: Need to make sure that pallets used for staging freight do not have protruding nails to prevent these types of unintentional relaeases from occurring.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: On 1/24/2017 it was discovered that an R&L Carriers trailer was leaking UN1263 Kal-Gard FA while stopped at a gas station in Eloy, AZ.  The trailer released approximately .5 gallon of material to the asphalt parking lot.  No soils, drains or waterways were impacted by the release.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to respond the release.  The contractor unloaded the trailer to discover that (30) 5 gallon steel pails of the material were damaged. It appeared as if the pails were crushed due to excessively heavy top loaded freight.  In total the damaged pails released approximately 2 gallons of material to the trailer floor and parking area.  The release was cleaned from the trailer floor and parking lot with absorbents and all waste containerized into a 55 gallon steel drum.  The damaged pails were overpacked into (7) 55 gallon steel drums and taken offsite for disposal.  The freight was then all reloaded onto the trailer and continued for shipping.

At 1302 hours on 01/13/2017, CSX Transportation personnel observed an intermittent drip release of material from the bottom outlet valve and secondary closure on tank car GATX 200259 in the Curtis Bay Yard, Baltimore, MD. CSX Transportation contracted HEPACO, LLC of Baltimore, MD to respond for assistance. Upon arrival, HEPACO, LLC response personnel observed the bottom outlet valve operating handle in a partially open position with no securement pin installed. HEPACO, LLC responders closed the valve, secured the required pin, and the release immediately stopped. It is estimated less than one gallon of material was released.

column58: Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: On 30 January 2017, at 1730 hours, personnel in the CSXT Tilford Yard discovered UTLX 208753, a loaded tank car of ETHANOL AND GASOLINE MIXTURE, leaking from the bottom of the car. The car was isolated and Quad County Corn Processors, NRC, Chemtrec and Georgia DEP were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2017-01-30-00171). HEPACO, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found an improperly closed bottom outlet valve handle and loose secondary plug. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Chad Conn via Chemtrec, shipper did not call carrier back. Contractor personnel closed the handle, tightened the plug and cleaned up the spill. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 required? No    Cause Code: 150 (5 points)  NARRI:5x(5+3+0)x(3+0)= 120

LEAKING PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED BY NORTHEAST DRIVER IN PACKAGE CAR. DRIVER CONTACTED THEIR CENTER. CENTER SUPERVISOR ESCORTED ME TO THE LEAKING PACKAGE TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL AND BRING BACK THE LEAKING PACKAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING. UPON EXAMINATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THE SHIPMENT WAS AN UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. I THEN CALLED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL HELP DESK TO REPORT THE PACKAGE (REFERENCE 856618). IT WAS ALSO DETERMINED THAT A CAP OF ONE OF THE EIGHT GALLONS WAS LOOSE (THERE WAS NO INNER SEAL UNDER THE CAP). APPROXIMATELY 1/2 GALLON LEAKED FROM ONE OF THE EIGHT CONTAINERS. I ALSO TOOK PICTURES FOR DOCUMENTATION AND PREPARED THE CONTENTS FOR FAA INSPECTION PER HAZMAT SUPPORT DESK.

column42: AEROSOLS, FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: JANUARY 12TH THE SHIPPER, SCORPION PROTECTIVE COATINGS, INC CONTACTED FEDEX TRADE NETWORKS OFFICE IN ELK GROVE VILLAGE,IL FOR AN AIR QUOTE FOR "NON HAZ PAINT RELATED MATERIAL.     JANUARY 20TH QUOTE ACCEPTED. SHIPMENT WAS SCHEDULED TO BE TENDERED TO A PASSENGER AIRLINE.  JANUARY 24TH FEDEX TRADE NETWORKS OFFICE IN ELK GROVE VILLAGE, IL RECEIVED THE FREIGHT ON ONE SKID VIA GROUND. WAREHOUSE SEPARATED THE SINGLE SKID INTO TWO SKIDS TO FIT ON THE PASSENGER AIRCRAFT. DURING THIS PROCESS, A RATTLING SOUND WAS DETECTED. BOXES HAD NO DANGEROUS GOODS LABELS OR HANDLING LABELS ATTACHED. WAREHOUSE EMPLOYEE OPENED A PACKAGE TO INSPECT THE CONTENTS TO VERIFY THEY MATCHED THE PAPERWORK. EMPLOYEE FOUND WHAT APPEARED TO BE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND STOPPED THE SHIPMENT. CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, AND THE SHIPPER CLAIMED TO NOT KNOW THE PRODUCTS WERE CONSIDERED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. SHIPPER SUPPLIED THE MSDS WHICH STATES IN SECTION 14: UN1950 AEROSOLS AND UN 1263 PAINT, CLASS 3 PACKING GROUP III.     JANUARY 26TH SHIPPER WAS INFORMED THAT THE PRODUCTS IN THE SHIPMENT WERE CONSIDERED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND ADVISED TO CONTACT A 3RD PARTY VENDOR TO PROPERLY CLASSIFY, PACKAGE, LABEL AND DOCUMENT THE PRODUCTS TO CONTINUE THE SHIPMENT.

The trailer was parked at a tankwash facility.  The tankwash personnel had it on their list to be cleaned but the trailer was not unloaded yet.  The tankwash personnel pulled it in the wash bay and saw that there was still security seals on the external valve and dome but cut the one off the valve and went to check for heel.  At this time they discovered the trailer was still loaded and pulled it back on the yard.  There must have been some residue in the valve and the cap wasn't fully secured allowing the 1 pint to leak out on the ground.  The driver who found it used spill pads to clean it up and notified the tankwash and Schneider personnel.
column169: We have reminded the tankwash personnel that any trailers that still have unbroken security seals should be questioned prior to cutting the seals as this could have been avoided.

column168: On 01/17/17 at 1436 hours (Eastern Time) it was reported at CSXT Goulding Yard, Pensacola, FL, that tank car AZXX32204, a loaded tank car of FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (ALPHA-PINENE, DIPENTENE), had product coming from the manway area.  Hepaco (CSX Hazmat Contractor) was dispatched to the scene.  Hepaco arrived onsite and confirmed product released from the manway onto the sides of the car.  Hepaco discovered that the 4 of 6 manway securement bolts were loose and unsecured. The shipper, International Paper Company (Doug Froehle 901-419-7984) was notified.      Hepaco secured the manway and installed a seal.  The car was released.        NAR Code: 200 (5 pts) Manway Bolts/ Nuts less than tool tight    5(5+3+3) x (2+0) = 110 NARRI         Pensacola, FL  01/17/2017  AZXX32204  FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS, N.O.S. (ALPHA-PINENE, DIPENTENE)

column168: On 1/31/17, an Empire Express tractor (15703) trailer (53810) was involved in a single vehicle jack knife accident along I-40 west bound near mile marker 271 in Lehi, AR. The accident caused the trailer to over turn on its side. The trailer was carrying (19) 1,000 kilogram plastic lined and plastic wrapped fiberboard gaylords of UN1689 sodium cyanide briquettes. The IBC containers and their lids were banded to the pallets on which they were loaded.  The accident caused the roof of the trailer to be torn open causing 12 of the 19 IBC containers to be released to the roadway and soil median.  The accident caused the lids of (6) of the IBCs to come off and release approximately 100 pounds of briquettes to the soil median.  No drains or waterways were impacted the release.  Due to the accident I-40 in both directions was shut down at approximately 0830 EST/0730 CST. I-40 east bound was closed for approximately 2 hours and I-40 west bound was completely closed for approximately 6 hours. The West Memphis, AR fire department initially responded to the release and secured the area. ERTS dispatched United States Environmental Service(USES) of Memphis, TN to respond to the release and perform clean up activities.  Due to the fact the a federal RQ was met (more than 1 pound of sodium cyanide was released to the environment) and that I-40 was closed due to the release, the NRC was notified and report number 1169902 was issued. USES personnel utilized a long reach fork lift and mini excavator to upright and load all undamaged IBCs onto a relief trailer.  The IBCs in which the lids had came off were re-secured with lids and banded back onto pallets. The re-secured IBCs were then loaded onto the relief trailer.  All spilled material was collected with the use of a vacuum truck and were stored in a vacuum box to avoid exposure to moisture. The re-secured IBCs and vacuum box of spilled material were transported back the Chemours Company in Memphis,TN for salvaging.  An approximate 20'x50' area of soil median was excavated to ensure that all spilled material had been collected.  Approximately 10 yards of impacted soil was taken offsite for disposal by USES personnel in a roll off box.    On 2/1/17 USES personnel returned to site to ensure that all spilled material had been collected. USES personnel assessed the area and determined that all material was recovered during the initial response.

column168: On 1/30/17, the rear trailer of two XPO Logistics trailers, trailer 3118318, was involved in a single trailer roll over accident on Strawberry Plains Pike while exiting I-40 east bound in Knoxville, TN. The first trailer or tractor did not roll over.  Due to the accident the lids of (6) 60 pound steel pails of UN1807 phosphoric anhydride came loose/were damaged causing the release of approximately 2 pounds of material to the trailer floor/wall.  The release was contained to the trailer and no soils, drains or waterways were impacted.  An environmental contractor was dispatched to respond to the release.  The damaged pails and spilled material were containerized into 55 gallon poly drums and transported to the XPO Logistics facility in Knoxville, TN by the contractor.  The trailer was uprighted and transported back to the Knoxville XPO facility for further clean up.  At the terminal it was determined that due to damaged suffered in the accident, an additional 7 pails needed to be over packed. In total, (13) 60 pound pails of the material were overpacked and held onsite for XPO personnel to manage. All spilled material and impacted debris was containerized into a 55 gallon poly drum as hazardous waste. The drum of waste was also staged at the XPO facility for XPO personnel to manage.

column168: It is believed that the reason for the spilled was that a damaged drum, one with a minor pin-hole was loaded half-way inside the trailer during the loading process.  The trailer was pre-loaded at the shipper and not supervised by the driver. Driver was fueling his truck when he noticed a small amount of liquid on his left side drive tires.  Driver completing fueling process and pulled to an area free of the fuel pumps, apx 200 feet away, and placed a spill pad on his drive tires to prevent leakage from hitting the ground.  Most of the material that was leaked was contained to the inside of the vehicle.  It was later determined that there was a small pin hole in the lower portion of the metal drum.  There is no telling how long the pin-hole leaked but it is judged to be from the point of loading until the point of being overpacked by the clean-up crew.  We do not know how long the drum had been on the trailer before our driver hooked to the trailer a couple of hours before the leak was discovered.  The spilled material was absorbed  with oil dry and the trailer clean, the leaking package wsa over-packed into a larger plastic drum
column169: The best way to of prevented this spill would have been for the shipper to take greater care to inspect packages at the time it was loaded onto the trailer.  Training  or instituting a step by step for inspecting and loading the drum onto pallets or the trailer floors would prevent many of this type leak.  It is believed that the shipper was slack in inspecting the containers before they were  loaded.

column168: I, John Vergis Environmental Officer for Wheeling and Lake Erie Railway, was called in at 0230 hours 0n 1-25-2017 for leaking car GATX 59159 in 33 track in Brewster. This leak was noticed by the Brewster Yard Car Inspector and then reported to the Brewster Yard Master.  He then notified me. When I got there to investigate I found that this car was not leaking.  The next car west, UTLX 5159 was leaking.  This car was leaking from the liquid valve on the A end.  I tried to tighten the valve to get the leak to stop but it would not.  I cracked the valve open and tried to reseal but only made it worse.  I was able to tighten the valve plug and get the leak to stop but the valve is still defective and the car will need tran-loaded.  I had the yardmaster shop the car and set to 4 new car shop.  Emergency Response Contractor Sunpro was called in the next day to look at the car.  They transferred the car and then flared the car off so that the valve could be replaced.  The valve was then replaced and the car bubble tested to 40 pounds with Nitrogen.  The bubble leak test passed and the car was released for service with the Nitrogen blanket remaining on the car.
column169: Better car securement procedures need followed.

column168: Carrier left shipper with CMTV loaded travel shot ways on highway, pulled into DOT scale house, DOT officer had carrier stop and officer informed carrier the trailer leaking. Carrier found small amount of product dipping from hose tube and in crash box. Carrier cleaned the spill areas. Carrier found the dome lid was leaking due to the gasket not seated. Carrier removed seal and reset the gasket and sealed dome. DOT office released carrier.     event 63299-1

No package failure -- Consignee equipment failure. Carrier at consignee off loading, the over head pipe that the product travels in busted and sprayed product on CMTV tractor/trailer and ground. Carrie shut down and informed consignee. Consignee wrapped the pipe and completed off loading. Consignee will make repairs to pipe. CMTV tractor/trailer was rinsed off and safe to travel.    event 63304-1

Carrier off loading CTMV at consignee, 10 minutes into it and noticed the hose leaking at the rear valve connection. Carrier shut down and found one of the dog ears on the connection opened and product sprayed out. Carrier removed the connection, resented the gasket, reconnected and completed off loading. Consignee cleaned the spilled area.     event 63316-1

Driver was pulling out of consignee location, when he noticed approximately 1/2 cup to 1 cup of the product had leaked from the top dome lid, onto the Asphalt.   A Mechanic came to the Tractor and trailer.  The mechanic inspected the Trailer and replaced the gasket on top dome lid to stop the leaking.        Event 63103

column168: An odor was detected coming from the car.  Inspection of the car revealed the A end liquid angle plug valve to be closed and the securement plug in position wrench tight with product leaking from the threaded plug.  Plug was partially unthreaded so that pipe sealant could be applied.  Plug was tightened back into place with no signs of further leakage.  With the valve closed, product was then noted leaking from the valve stem packing gland nut. The nut was loosened, and additional Teflon packing was added to the valve stem.  The packing gland nut was retightened which secured the car from further release.  Due to a faulty valve, on 1-11-17 product from car UTLX 951233 was transloaded into tank car UTLX 951242 at the Alexander Railyard.  Upon completion of the transfer, car was placed back into transportation and car UTLX 951233 was home shopped for further repairs.
column169: Conduct proper pre and post inspection of car upon completion of loading or unloading, to ensure all valves, fittings and closures are in a closed and secure condition preventing release of liquid, vapor or gas while car is in transportation.

column168: CAME IN TO WORK. TWILIGHT SORT HAD THIS PACKAGE SITTING ON TABLE. HE TOLD ME THAT SOMEONE DROPPED IT OFF IN FRONT OF THE CAGE AND HE FOUND IT WHEN HE RETURNED TO CAGE FROM ANOTHER CALL. HE RESPONDED TO IT USING THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS.

RESPONDED TO A LEAKING PACKAGE. UPON INSPECTION, FOUND FULLY REGULATED CLASS 3 HAZMAT, WITH 17 SAMPLES OF FINGER NAIL POLISH. 3 OF THE 17 SAMPLES LEAKED DUE TO POOR PACKAGING. CONTENTS WERE PACKED AGAINST OTHER CONTENTS WITH NO PADDING BETWEEN ITEMS, CAUSING 3 SAMPLE CUPS TO CRACK. THE LEAK SOILED THE OUTER PACKAGING. CONTENTS HELD FOR REGULATORY INSPECTION.
PACKAGE WAS FOUND DAMP. UPON INSPECTION PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING FROM CAP. NO INTERNAL PACKING TO PROTECT THE PACKAGE FROM ANY KIND OF IMPACT. SOFT PLASTIC CONTAINER UNFIT TO HOLD 5 GALLONS

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: 4 pallets (12 lead acid batteries shrink-wrapped to each pallet with wood furring strips nailed around the perimeter of each pallet) loaded on to removable flatbed for transport from Minneapolis to Fargo by way of Sioux Falls. At Sioux Falls, flatbed was slid off truck using articulating arm and set on ground to conduct other work.  Freezing rain that night created ice on flatbed.  Next morning flatbed was slid up on truck with articulating arm. One pallet of batteries slid down removable flatbed as it was being pulled up on to the truck and hit the ground.  Eight batteries broke/cracked releasing about 12 gallons of sulfuric acid on to ground.  Baking soda used to neutralize acid.  Broken batteries and rock/soil (approximately 4 cubic feet - 2' x3' x 8") were placed into 3 poly drums (1 drum for rock/soil and two drums for broken batteries).  Sample of rock/soil was collected and is being tested for lead to determine proper disposal.  Once results are received the containerized material will be sent to Xcel's Chestnut facility for proper disposal
column169: Discuss incident in future training events.  Make sure straps are tight enough to hold cargo down. Use straps to tie down the actual pallets as well as the cargo on the pallets if there is concern of damaging the cargo by over-tightening of straps.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, LOW SPECIFIC ACTIVITY (LSA-I) NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: BELOW ARE THE KNOWN DETAILS OF THE SHIPMENT OF URANIUM ORE CONCENTRATES FROM HONEYWELL METROPOLIS TO ENERGY FUELS.     ON JANUARY 6, 2017, TRAILER # 7543 WAS LOADED WITH 55 DRUMS OF URANIUM ORE CONCENTRATES WITH A TOTAL WEIGHT OF 36,628 POUNDS. THE LOADING OCCURRED AT HONEYWELL'S FACILITY AT 2768 US HWY 45 NORTH IN METROPOLIS, IL. THE DRUMS IN THE SHIPMENT WERE SMEARED BY HEALTH PHYSICS PERSONNEL, CLEARED FOR SHIPMENT, AND LOADED INTO A PLASTIC LINED, ENCLOSED TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS SHIPPED FROM METROPOLIS, IL ON JANUARY 10,2017 as UN 2912 RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, LSA-1. ON JANUARY 12, 2017, HONEYWELL WAS NOTIFIED BY THE RECIPIENT, ENERGY FUELS (6425 HIGHWAY 191, BLANDING, UT), THAT UPON REMOVING THE DRUMS FROM THE TRAILER (PACKAGE), THERE WERE VISIBLE SIGNS OF CONTAMINATION IN AND ON THE UNDERCARRIAGE OF THE TRAILER. THE PLASTIC LINING INSIDE THE TRAILER WAS RIPPED IN ONE LOCATION; THE CONTAMINATION WAS EVIDENT I THAT LOCATION. CONTAMINATION WAS EVIDENT ON DRUM THAT HAS BEEN IN THAT LOCATION OF THE RIPPED PLASTIC. ENERGY FUELS DETECTED TOTAL ALPHA CONTAMINATION ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER OF 29,400 DPM/100CM AND TOTAL ALPHA CONTAMINATION UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER (EXTERIOR) OF 1,470 DPM/100CM. ENERGY FUELS IS IN THE PROCESS OF DECONTAMINATING THE TRAILER ON JANUARY 13, 2017. DUE TO THE VISIBLE CONTAMINATION ON THE EXTERIOR OF THE PACKAGE (TRAILER), HONEYWELL NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND USNRC REGION II REGARDING THE INCIDENT.
column169: FOR PENDING AND FUTURE SHIPMENTS, HONEYWELL IMMEDIATELY BEGAN MORE STRINGENT INSPECTIONS OF THE BOTTOMS OF DRUMS BEING PREPARED FOR SHIPMENT. ASIDE FROM DRUM INTEGRITY, PERSONNEL BEGAN LOOKING FOR ITEMS THAT MIGHT HAVE PUNCTURED OR BECOME ATTACHED TO THE BOTTOM OF A DRUM. ADDITIONALLY, UPON LOADING, THE PRE-LOAD STAGING AREAS WERE INSPECTED FOR ANY SIGNS OF CONTAMINATION.     A MORE IN-DEPTH INVESTIGATION WAS IMITATED ON JANUARY 16, 2017. RESULTS OF THAT INVESTIGATION ARE NOT YET AVAILABLE.

ON 1/17/2017 AT 0900 HOURS CST, I WAS ADVISED OF A TANK CAR LEAKING AT THE INDIAN HARBOR BELT(IHB) RAILROAD YARD LOCATED IN RIVERDALE, IL. IHB TERMINAL SUPERINTENDENT STEVE DUNN ADVISED CAR NUMBER PROX 303136, CONTAINING A FULL LOAD OF HYDROCARBONS, LIQUIDS NOS (NATURAL GASOLINE) UN 3295 PG 1 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING BY AN IHB CAR DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEE. MULTIPLE ADJACENT TRACKS WERE TAKING OUT OF SERVICE DUE TO THE VAPOR AND FLAMMABILITY OF THE PRODUCT.     UPON ARRIVAL MYSELF AND CONNOR SCHAEFFER OF SUNPRO INSPECTED THE CAR AND NOTICED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE FLANGE BOLTS THAT SECURE THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP TO THE VALVE. CONNOR OF SUNPRO USED A ADJUSTABLE WRENCH AND TIGHTENED 3 OF THE 4 FLANGE BOLTS. THE 3 BOLTS SHOULD HAVE BEEN TOOL TIGHT BUT WERE EXTREMELY LOOSE. AFTER THE 3 BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED THE LEAK STOPPED. WHERE THE LEAKING WAS COMING FROM WAS BELOW THE VALVE SO THAT MEANT THAT THE VALVE WAS NOT FUNCTIONING PROPERLY. THE CAR WAS SUBSEQUENTLY MOVED TO ANOTHER TRACK WHERE WE WILL EVENTUALLY TRANSFER THE PRODUCT INTO ANOTHER COMPARABLE TANK CAR. THE DURATION OF THE LEAK IS UNKNOWN AS WELL AS HOW MUCH PRODUCT LOSS IS UNKNOWN. THE CAR WAS IN ROUTE TO NUSTAR IN BLUE ISLAND IL.
column169: SPOKE WITH KEVIN HIGGINS OF MARKWEST ENERGY PARTNERS, LP WHO ADVISED THEY WILL CONTINUE TO USE PROPER PRE-SHIPMENT INSPECTIONS IN ORDER TO MITIGATE A PROBLEM LIKE THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE.

column168: Event/Claim # 63199    Driver and consignee employee noticed that the product was not moving into the consignee's tank. Driver closed internal and external valves. Driver hooked air supply line to blow down valve and discovered no air was going through. Customer removed the air supply line from the blow down valve, but the blow down valve was still open. Product sprayed onto driver and ground. Approximately 4 - 5 gallons spilled on the concrete.      There was no package failure.    It took less than a minute for the product that was in the line to be released onto the ground.    The consignee employee cleaned up the spill with absorbent pads.

column162: SVP HEALTH, SAFETY AND TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE
column168: Material was packed into a Super Sack which was then left outside, unprotected where it was exposed to rain and snow. Prior to pickup, there had been a snow storm. The unprotected package collected an accumulation of snow on the upper surface of the package. As the snow melted, water infiltrated the package and subsequently passed through the contained material eventually releasing a small amount of liquid. After donning appropriate PPE, facility employees used absorbents to collect the leaked material which were properly disposed of. The package was monitored for further leakage, none was discovered. The package was overwrapped as a precaution and shipped to its final destination without further incident.
column169: Conversations were held with both the shipper and facility personnel with regard to proper storage and shipment of material. Going forward, material will be protected from the elements. Further Drivers have been instructed to carefully evaluate any material stored outside for evidence of water infiltration and refuse any shipment found to be suspect.

column168: Approximately 5000 liquid pounds of UN3257 refined petroleum based asphalt leaked from the manway cover on a 307/407 CTMV due to damage caused by a single vehicle rollover accident. The release impacted the asphalt roadway and migrated onto the soil median and a concrete lined ditch in the median. The overturned vehicle blocked 3 lanes of traffic and traffic was directed around the accident using the right emergency lane. An environmental contractor responded and performed cleanup activities. The impacted soil was scraped with a skidsteer and containerized for proper disposal. The excavated area was back filled and restored to pre-spill conditions.

Event/Claim # 63154     Our driver pulled the CTMV onto the scale.. The shipper's weigh-in operator noticed product coming from the air vent..  Our driver manually closed the air vent..      The trailer is equipped with an air-actuated vent valve at the top of the tank, which is controlled by a ground-level air switch and powered by trailer air-brake air.. The release was due to sloshing and it stopped when the trailer was stopped and product stopped surging..  The remote-controlled vent was switched off, but did not close..       No more than two (2) minutes passed from the time the product release was noticed until the air vent was closed..      The air vent was closed manually, which prevented further release.. Subsequent inspection failed to find a fault in the vent mechanism, or the actuator system..

DRIVER WAS OFFLOADING INTO CONSIGNEE'S TOTE. DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE CONSIGNEE'S TOTE WAS LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM SO HE SHUT DOWN, NOTIFIED CONSIGNEE AND BEGAN PLACING SPILL PADS DOWN. DRIVER AND CONSIGNEE CLEANED UP SPILL USING SPILL KIT, SPILL PADS AND SAND. LATER INVESTIGATION DISCOVERED THAT THE TOTE WAS DAMAGED PREVIOUSLY BY A FORK LIFT. EVENT #63256-1.

column168: On January 19, 2017 Land O Lakes Oil Company, from Kimball Mn, was delivering a tanker of diesel fuel to GNP.  Their tractor broke down on the trip and they swapped it out for a spare.  The driver began to pump the fuel off the truck as normal or so he thought.  It turns out the hydraulics between tractors were the direct opposite.  So rather than pumping fuel off the truck, the driver was sucking fuel from the tank back onto the truck.  The compartment on the truck filled and discharged fuel out of the vent ports.  The driver promptly shut down the pump, but we calculated 96 gallons of fuel was discharged onto the ground.  GNP utilized spill kits and wood shavings in an effort to absorb the spill.  It was a warm day with a lot of snowmelt, so the discharge spread rather rapidly.  Glen Winter, Owner of Land O Lakes notified the MPCA duty officer of the discharge, case # 163822.  West Central Environmental Consultants were contacted to handle the cleanup.  They were on site 1/19/17 as well as 1/20/17.  They collected fuel soaked shavings as well as some soil and have it stored in a lined roll off container.  West Central is handling the case at this point.

column168: At the end of the unloading process, our driver discovered hazardous material releasing from the CTMV's crash box drain hose. Sloshing only upon entering consignee location caused the hazardous material to release from the dome lid into the crash box. The release is estimated to be less than 90 minutes in duration, based on the time taken to complete the delivery.     Upon inspection by a mechanic, the dome gasket was found to be deteriorated and replaced.     Event # 63170

On 01/31/2017 at 11:43, the FRA in the CSXT Uceta Yard discovered CBTX 743360, a residue tank car of Alcohols N.O.S. Ethanol, leaking from the top of the car.  The car was isolated and the shipper, Koch Supply and Trading Company, the Florida State Watch Office (report number 2017-958), and the NRC (report number 1169921) were notified.  CHEMTREC report number  2017-01-31-00166).  Hulls Environmental, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the car to have eight of eight manway bolts less than tool tight.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper (Shamryn Holzwarth, phone number 316-828-7348).  Contractor personnel tightened the manway bolts and noted the product had a vapor release.  The leak was secured and the car was released for transport.  This incident did not require a special switching move or a 7.1.     The shipper on the waybill is listed as Koch Supply and Trading Company.  The car was unloaded and released into transportation by TRANSFLO / Arrow Material Services (Contact Tim Moore 813-294-9926).     Cause Code: 200 (point value 5)   NARRI Severity Index: 70

column168: Event/Claim # 63191..    Driver connected the consignee's hose to the CTMV discharge and opened the discharge valves. Driver and consignee employee were watching the pump and noticed the product was not flowing into the storage tank. Driver closed the valve while the consignee employee checked the pump. Consignee employee pulled the cam locks off the hose and product sprayed onto the consignee employee.  Consignee employee went to shower immediately to clean off.     There was no package failure.  No holes, cracks, etc. in the hose that caused the release.     It took no more than a few seconds for the product  in the line to be released. There was no further release of product.     Another consignee employee discovered the valve on the consignee's end had been closed.

column168: Hilco driver was unloading Diesel fuel into underground storage tank at the Speedway gas station. In the process of unloading the driver used the veeder root fuel management system on site (computer system) to determine that fuel would fit into the two diesel fuel tanks. He approximated the split amount that would need to go into the two tanks. After dropping the fuel into the first tank he then started to drop fuel into the second tank. After dropping the fuel into the second tank fuel came back out the open port on the first tank allowing approx 20 gallons to bubble out onto the pavement and then the fuel ran toward a storm drain. A small amount of fuel dribbled into the catch basin of the storm sewer. The driver put down pads to keep any more fuel from going into the storm sewer and called dispatch office for assistance. Fire Dept responded until outside environmental contractor could respond to complete clean-up. Actual fuel spill lasted approx 3 minutes. Scene was cleaned up within approx 3 hours. It was later discovered that Veeder Root system showed more available space in the two diesel tanks that was what was actually available.
column169: Ensure Veeder Root system is accurate so that metrics are accurate before unloading fuel.

column168: CITX 220073 was discovered leaking during a routine train inspection in Sioux City, IA.  BNSF mechanical reported that the car was leaking out of the bottom outlet cap and the cap was secure.  HMRI was called to respond to the release. The valve was cycled and the BOV was still leaking drops of product. The BOV cap was secured using Teflon tape which stopped the leak with the secondary closure.  The product will be transferred to a residue Ethanol tank car provided by the shipper.
column169: The shipper (Poet) should review the loading and inspection procedures with the loading/unloading rack crews to make sure all parties understand the importance of preventing non-accidental releases of hazardous materials in transit.  Recommend checking a loaded car BOV for leakage by removing the BOV cap to check after car is loaded.

column168: Non-Preventable - Head On Collision - The other party lost control and swerved in the Eagle drivers lane resulting in a head on collision. The impact separated the tanker from the tractor, spun the tractor and laid the tanker on its side on the SE  travel lane shoulder. Slow petroleum leakage was observed from the dome covers. Petroleum was reported to have impacted the roadway and shoulder. Waterways were not impacted. Emergency authorities responded and the SC Department of Health and Action Environmental managed the spill clean up on behalf of Eagle Transport. Potentially 400-500 gallons were lost to the nearby road shoulder. Soil has now been excavated.    ***The fatality was due to the impact of the head on collision and was not related to the product.
column169: There was nothing our driver could have done to prevented this accident & product spill.

column168: TILX 111624 was reported to have a vapor cloud coming from the top of it. The car was in the Roseville bowl, track 30. Roseville Fire Hazmat team assisted with the response. FD# 171355. On the first entry to inspect the tank car, about 2 cups of hydrochloric acid was observed in the protective housing on the pressure plate and a small vapor cloud was coming from it. On the second entry the acid was neutralized. The liquid line blind flange had 4 out of 4 bolts less then tool tight. The air line blind flange had 3 out of 4 bolts that were less then tool tight. The fill hole had 1 out of 3 bolts that were less then tool tight. All bolts were secured. The car was no longer releasing.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO AVOID VEHICLE IN ROADWAY, RESULTING IN A ROLL-OVER ACCIDENT. column168: A Clean harbors Environmental Services Inc. van trailer containing hazardous materials arrived at the Linden, NJ transfer facility, a final destination for the material to be reprocessed. While unloading, the driver noticed that there was a  leaking 55 gallon drum on the truck. A response crew was notified, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the truck and inspected the leaking drum; the drum was found to have a loose bung. The bung was tightened correctly. The exterior of the drum and trailer floor were fully cleaned and re-mediated. The trailer was returned to service, and the drum staged for processing. This release was reported to the NJ DEP at 6:46pm on 1/20/17, to Operator 76, report number 170120184330.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed. This release was the direct result of improper container closure, and insufficient container inspection prior to transport. The driver will be retrained on proper container inspection, and proper container closure procedures using the manufacturers drum specific closure instructions. The shipper was notified and advised to use proper container closure procedures using the manufacturers drum specific closure instructions.

column168: ON FRIDAY JANUARY 13, 2017. EMPLOYEE 1 REPRESENTING THE CARRIER PICKED UP 10-55 GALLON 1A1 AND 8- 55 GALLON 1H2 CONTAINERS FROM CLARIANT CORPORATION IN LOUISVILLE, KY.IT WAS RAINING THAT DAY, AND THE CONTAINERS WERE STAGED OUTSIDE. THIS CAUSED THE DRUMS TO BE WET. THE CONTAINERS WERE LOADED WITH A PALLET JACK ONTO A HERITAGE TRANSPORT, LLC SHORT RUCK AND DELIVERED TO THE 10 DAY TRANSFER FACILITY WHERE THEY REMAINED ON THE VEHICLE UNTIL MONDAY 1/16/2017. AN EMPLOYEE OFFLOADED THE CONTAINERS FROM THE VEHICLE AND STAGED THE CONTAINERS ON A CONCRETE FLOOR INSIDE THE 10 DAY TRANSFER WAREHOUSE, THAT MORNING (AT APPROXIMATELY 08:00) TO CHECK THE CONTAINERS, APPLY COMPANY BAR CODES AND PREFORM INTERNAL COMPANY PROCEDURES FOR THE CONTAINERS TO TRANSFER TO THE DESTINATION FACILITY. WHILE THE CONTAINERS WHERE STAGED IN THE WAREHOUSE, EMPLOYEE 2 OBSERVED (AT APPROXIMATELY 08:30) THAT ONE OF THE 55 1A1 CONTAINERS HAD BEGUN TO LEAK. APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO THE CONCRETE FLOOR INSIDE THE WAREHOUSE BUILDING. EMPLOYEE 2 OBSERVING THE LEAK FORM THE CONTAINER NOTIFIED EMPLOYEE 1 WHO RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY WITH A SPILL KIT AND SUPPLIES. EMPLOYEE 1 USED A BAG OF VERMICULITE TO ABSORBED THE MATERIAL ON THE CONCRETE FLOOR, WHILE EMPLOYEE 2 STAGED AN OVER PACK CONTAINER (85 GALLON 1A1) INTO PLACE. BEFORE OVER PACKING THE CONTAINER, EMPLOYEE 1 WAS ABLE TO SPECULATE THAT THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE A PIN HOLE ON A WELD LOCATED AT THE BASE OF THE CONTAINER. USING A DRUM SLING AND FORKLIFT, THE TWO EMPLOYEES IMMEDIATELY OVER PACKED THE LEAKING CONTAINER. THE VERMICULITE MATERIAL WAS THEN SWEPT UP AND PLACED INTO THE SAME OVER PACK CONTAINER WHICH WAS THEN SEALED AND CLOSED.     ON WEDNESDAY JANUARY 18 2017 AT APPROXIMATELY 10:00 EMPLOYEE 1 WAS INSPECTING THE CONTAINERS PICKED UP ON JANUARY 13, 2017. EMPLOYEE 1 OBSERVED A SECOND 55 GALLON 1A1 DRUM LEAKING FROM THE WELD AT THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER. APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON OF MATERIAL SPILLED ONTO THE CONCRETE FLOOR INSIDE THE WAREHOUSE. EMPLOYEE 1 NOTIFIED EMPLOYEE 3 DONNED APPROPRIATE PPE AND PROCEEDED WITH THE SHILL RESPONSE. A PLOY OVER PACK DRUM WAS USED OT OVER PACK THE LEAKING STEEL DRUM IN A MANNER SIMILAR TO THAT VERMICULITE WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED INSIDE THE OVER PACK DRUM. BECAUSE TWO OF THE CONTAINERS LEAKED. HERITAGE TRANSPORT LLC REPRESENTATIVES OVER PACKED EACH OF THE EIGHTEEN CONTAINERS ASSOCIATED WITH THE CONSIGNMENTS AS A PREVENTIVE MEASURE.
column169: THE PROBABLE CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WAS FOUND TO HAVE BEEN AN AQUEOUS HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WITH A PH OF 1 TO 3 THAT WAS PLACED INSIDE STEEL CONTAINERS. THIS LIKELY CAUSED THE MATERIAL TO DETERIORATE THE STEEL WHICH RESULTED IN THE MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE PACKAGES. THE INCIDENT AND PROBABLE CAUSE WAS COMMUNICATED TO THE SHIPPER ALONG WITH GUIDANCE TO ONLY USE AND SHIP THE MATERIAL IN 55 1H1 DRUMS TO ENSURE THAT THE DETERIORATION OF THE CONTAINER WILL NO OCCUR WHEN SHIPPING A MATERIAL. USING A FIBER CONTAINER SHOULD MITIGATE THE LIKELIHOOD OF A CONTAINER FAILURE LEADING TO LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WHILE IN TRANSIT THE CARRIER'S INTERNAL INFORMATION MANAGEMENT SYSTEM SPECIFIC TO THE CONSIGNED MATERIAL WAS UPDATED TO INDICATE THAT ONLY FIBER CONTAINERS WOULD BE ACCEPTED.    THE PROBABLE ADMINISTRATIVE ROOT CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WAS LIKELY TO BE THAT TRAINING SYSTEMS, TASK INSTRUCTION AND MANAGEMENT INVOLVEMENT OF THE COMPANY HIPPING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MAY HAVE LED TO THE MATERIAL BEING PLACED IN INCOMPATIBLE PERFORMANCE PACKAGING, WHICH LED TO THE FAILURE OF THE PACKAGING AND LEAKING OF THE MATERIAL.

column168: DRIVER UNLOADED 1000 GALLONS OF PREMIUM GASOLINE FIRST, THEN DRIVER SAID HE PUT THE CAP & LID BACK ON THE PREMIUM FILL. HE PROCEEDED TO HOOK UP HOSE TO REGULAR GASOLINE DROP WITHOUT INCIDENT. ALL PRODUCT WAS UNLOADED INTO THE TANK. DRIVER FAILED TO HOOK UP VAPOR RECOVERY, CAUSING PRODUCT IN PREMIUM TANK TO PUSH OUT OF DROP TUBE RESULTING IN SPILLAGE OF APPROXIMATELY 550 GALLONS OF PREMIUM GASOLINE. DRIVER USED SPILL PADS AND TOOK NECESSARY ACTIONS FOR REQUESTING RESPONSE & CLEANUP. NO PRODUCT CONTAMINATED ANY WATER SUPPLY, BUT WENT IN DITCH LINE & WAS REMOVED & CLEANED UP BY AN ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CREW.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: TERMINAL MANAGER NOTIFIED AT 08:45 BY THE SECURITY GATE AT FMI CLAYPOOL, AZ THAT ONE BULK TRANSPORTATION'S CARGO TANKS WAS LEAKING SULFURIC ACID ON THE GROUND. INVESTIGATION DETERMINED DRIVER OF TRUCK 3278 AND CARGO TANK TRAILER 7976 WAS LEAKING. CALLS TO DRIVERS MOBILE PHONE YIELDED NO ANSWER, SO PEOPLENET'S TELEMATICS WAS USED TO SEND MESSAGE TO DRIVER TO STOP THE VEHICLE COMBINATION AND TO CALL DISPATCH. THE DRIVER PULLED OFF THE ROAD AND CHECKED HER DOME LID. FOUND DIPSTICK CHAIN OBSTRUCTING THE SEAL BETWEEN THE DOME LID GASKET AND THE MANHOLE. DRIVER OPENED DOME, REMOVED CHAIN PINCHED BETWEEN THE DOME GASKET AND MANHOLE AND RESEALED THE DOME LID. DRIVER ERROR. DRIVER CORRECTED THE ISSUE AND THEN PROCEEDED TO MM 249 ON HWY 70 AND PULLED OF INTO A PULL OFF AREA. DRIVER WAS TOLD TO NOT MOVE THE TRUCK AND TRAILER. UPON ARRIVAL TERMINAL MANAGER INTERFACED WITH AZDPS. BULK MECHANIC CHECK TRAILING EQUIPMENT. DETERMINATION WAS THAT ROOT CAUSE OF SPILL HAD BEEN ADDRESSED. AZDPS RELEASED EQUIPMENT AND A NEW DRIVER WAS ASSIGNED TO DELIVER THE PRODUCT TO ITS DESTINATION. OFFENDING DRIVER TAKEN FOR POST INCIDENT DRUG & ALCOHOL TEST AND SUSPENDED PENDING INVESTIGATION. OFFENDING DRIVER WAS TERMINATED IN DAYS FOLLOWING.     BULK VP SAFETY FRANK CUTTER CONTACTED AT 9:00 A.M RECEIVED CALLS FROM TRI CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, AZDPS, ADOT AND CUSTOMER. COORDINATED AND MADE ARRANGEMENTS ANSWERING AUTHORITIES AND ARRANGING FOR SITE CLEAN UP. ADOT MANAGED TRAFFIC AND PARTIAL LANE CLOSURES. ARIZONA EASTERN RAIL ROAD CONTACTED BY BULK AS PRODUCT WAS SPILLED ON THEIR RAIL CROSSING AND TESTING WAS RECOMMENDED. ROADWAY NEUTRALIZED BY 17:30 AS APPROVED BY ADOT.    REMEDIATION OF ROADWAY WAS COMPLETED TUESDAY 1/13/2017 @ 17:50 HOURS.
column169: RE: CORRECTION ACTION PLAN- JANUARY 28, 2017 SULFURIC ACID SPILL:    1) UPDATED SOP'S FOR BULK-FMI LOADING AND UNLOADING. THESE REVISIONS WERE REVIEWED AT THE SAFETY MEETING THIS WEEKEND AS PART OF OUR ONGOING TRAINING AS WELL AS USED FOR TRAINING/REVIEW WITH NEW HIRES. THE DRIVER INVOLVED HAS BEEN TERMINATED.     2) WE WILL MOVE FORWARD WITH REPLACEMENT OF THE DIPSTICK CHAIN WITH WIRE CABLE ON ALL CARGO TANKS SERVICING FMI. THIS IS TO BE COMPLETED BY 3/3/2017 WITH A FINAL LIST PROVIDED NOTING DATE OF COMPLETED BY EACH CARGO TANK ASSET NUMBER.     3) TRAINING DOCUMENT REVIEWED BY ALL DRIVERS OF OCCURRENCE AND SOP WITH EACH DRIVER TO SIGN AS ACKNOWLEDGMENT OF THE EMPHASIS TO BE PLACED ON PREVENTION OF DOME SEAL OBSTRUCTIONS.     4) VIA PEOPLENET, WE WILL BROADCAST MESSAGE REMINDING DRIVERS SERVICING FMI TO DOUBLE CHECK THE DOME TO MANHOLE SEAL FOR ANY OBSTRUCTIONS AFTER LOADING.    5) IMPROVE CONTACT RELATIONSHIP WITH CONTRACTOR ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE, INC.        A. PRIMARY CONTACT AND I NOW HAVE ONE ANTHER'S DIRECT MOBILE PHONE NUMBERS AND ALTERNATIVELY EMAILS IN ORDER TO EXPEDITE VIA PHONE, TEXT AND EMAIL.

ON JANUARY 18,2017 THE IMPACT CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGIES, INC. DELIVERY TRUCK WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON HWY 25 APPROXIMATELY 12 MILES SOUTH OF COLBY, KANSAS WHEN THE RIGHT TIRES OF THE TRUCK LEFT THE ROADWAY AND THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AND EVENTUALLY ROLLED THE TRUCK ON TO THE SOUTH BOUND LANE. DURING THE ROLLOVER THE CHEMICAL TOTES WERE CRUSHED AND DISPLACED INTO THE HIGHWAY RIGHT OF THE WAY ON THE WEST SIDE OF HWY 25. THE CHEMICAL TOTES WERE EITHER COMPLETELY CRUSHED DUE TO IMPACT OR SUFFERED LARGE HOLES THAT ALLOWED THE CHEMICAL TO RELEASE. THE DURATION OF RELEASE WAS INSTANT DUE TO THE IMPACT THE TRUCK MADE WITH THE ROAD AND DID NOT OCCUR OVER A LONG-TIME FRAME.     AFTER THE INCIDENT OCCURRED, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND EMS WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE, THE IMPACT CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGIES. INC. EMPLOYEE WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE HOSPITAL DUE TO INJURIES SUFFERED FROM THE CRASH. THE ROADWAY WAS CLEANED UP AND RE-OPENED. THE AREA AROUND TH SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND NOT DEEMED A THREAT TO HUMAN HEALTH OR ANY WATER WAYS. IMPACT CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGIES, INC. CONTRACTED OUT AN EMERGENCY CLEANUP CREW, HAZ-MAT RESPONSE, TO THE SCENE. HAZ-MAT RESPONSE IS AN EMERGENCY CLEANUP COMPANY OUT OF GREAT BEND, KS.     HAZ-MAT RESPONSE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND TRANSFERRED ALL REMAINING CHEMICAL INTO NEW CONTAINERS AND REMOVED THE DAMAGED TOTES INTO  ROLL-OFF BOX. THE IMPACTED AREA WAS CONTAINED AND MARKED. IMPACT CHEMICAL TECHNOLOGIES AND HAZ-MAT RESPONSE WORKED WITH KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH & ENVIRONMENT(KDHE), THOMAS COUNTY LEPC AND KANSAS DOT DURING THE CLEANUP EFFORTS. THIS SPILL INVOLVED METHANOL, SO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WAS INFORMED ON JANUARY 18, 2017    WITH INCLEMENT WEATHER(F0G) AND DOT SCHEDULING, AND SINCE THIS RELEASE WAS NOT A THREAT TO HUMAN HEALTH OR ANY WATER WAYS, THE EXCAVATION OF THE IMPACTED SOIL WAS PERFORMED ON JANUARY 24, 2017. THE IMPACTED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND TRANSPORTED BY HAZ-MAT RESPONSE TO THEIR FACILITY TO BE PROFILED AND DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO STATE AND GOVERNMENT REGULATIONS. THIS WAS COORDINATED WITH THE KANSAS DOT, THOMAS COUNTY LEPC, AND KANSAS DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH & ENVIRONMENT. SINCE VALUES FOR PART IV(CONSEQUENCES-DAMAGES) IS NOT AVAILABLE AT THE TIME, A FOLLOW-UP REPORT WILL BE PROVIDED.

column168: THE EXPI CREW DEPARTING EAST PEORIA, IL RAIL YARD HEADING EAST BOUND IN ROUTE TO LAFAYETTE, IN DERAILED THE LAST 2 CARS OF THE TRAIN(ACFX 200437 AND TCBX 193708) IN THE VICINITY OF TRACK 21 AND THE MAINLINE. TRAINMASTER LOUIS GARRETT AND ASSISTANT GENERAL MANAGER MITCH BROWN WERE STANDING AT THE HEAD END OF THE TRAIN ON THE NORTH SIDE OD THE TRACK WATCHING A CLASS 1 AIR BRAKE RELEASE TEST  AS THE TRAIN WAS ROLLING BY. AGM BROWN NOTICED THE REAR CAR WAS LEANING FORWARD AND ORDERED TRAINMASTER GARRETT TO STOP THE TRAIN. TRAINMASTER GARRETT IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE TPW 3441 AND ORDERED THE TRAIN TO STOP. CARS WERE MOVED APPROXIMATELY 350 FEET BEFORE TRAIN WAS PLACED IN EMERGENCY. REAR OF TRAIN CAME TO A STOP IN THE VICINITY OF THE KROGER SWITCH AT THE EAST END OF THE YARD AT APPROXIMATELY MP 107. THE LAST CAR OF THE TRAIN(ACFX 200437) WAS LEANING FORWARD WITH THE FRONT TRUCK HAVING SLID HALFWAY DOWN THE CAR BODY.THE TRUCK HAD SHEARED THE BOTTOM BELLY TANK VALVE OF THE CAR CAUSING DENATURED ALCOHOL TO BE RELEASED FROM THE CAR. 911, CHEMTECH, NRC,FRA,EPA, AND ARDC WERE ALL NOTIFIED AND THE AREA WAS EVACUATED AND THE SPILL CONTAINED. ONE CAR WITH A FUNCTIONAL HAND BRAKE (CTCX 733245) WAS CUT AWAY TO HOLD THE 2 DAMAGED CARS AND THE TRAIN DEPARTED AGAIN IN ROUTE TO LAFAYETTE, IN.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS TRANSPORTING A LOAD OF #2 DIESEL FUEL FROM HOLLY FRONTIER IN CHEYENNE, WYOMING TO THE TA234 SITE IN RAWLINS, WY. THE WEATHER TURNED INTO SNOW AND ICE ON THE ROADWAY AND AS OUR DRIVER APPROACHED A DOWNHILL SECTION, HE NOTICED AN ACCIDENT INVOLVING MULTIPLE VEHICLES AHEAD OF HIM. HE SLOWED HIS SPEED AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE IN THE RIGHT HAND LANE. DURING THE DECELERATION, THE TRAILER STARTED TO SLIP AND BREAK LOOSE SEVERAL TIMES. WHEN THE DRIVER GOT CLOSE TO THE TRUCK IN FRONT OF HIM, HE WAS FORCED TO MOVE INTO THE LEFT HAND LANE BECAUSE HE COULD NOT SLOWDOWN QUICKLY ENOUGH BEFORE THE ACCIDENT. WHEN HE WAS NEXT TO THE TRUCK. THIS CAUSED A VERTICAL CRACK IN ONE OF THE BULKHEADS ON TRAILER CAUSING IT TO  START POURING FUEL OUT. DRIVER PULLED OVER ON ROADSIDE AND HOOKED UP HIS PUMP TO PUMP THE LEAKING COMPARTMENTS FUEL INTO ANOTHER ONE, NOT LEAKING WITHIN MINUTES. DISPATCH INFORMED STATE PATROL. EPA, PERS & DEQ IMMEDIATELY.
column169: TRY TO ASSESS WEATHER CONDITIONS BETTER.

column168: THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK, A 2700 GALLON, 5 COMPARTMENT DELIVERY TRUCK WAS DELIVERY FUEL TO AN UNDERGROUND FUEL TANK. PLACE HOSE FROM TRUCK INTO FILL PIPE ON TANK. WHEN THE TANK WAS FILLED, IT SHUT OFF THE FLOW WHEN THE TANKS OVERFILL PROTECTION DEVICE SHUT OFF. WHEN FLOW INTO TANK STOPPED IT FLOWED OUT OF THE FILL PIPE WHERE THE FILL VALVE ON THE HOSE DID NOT SHUT DOWN UNTIL THE OPERATOR SAW FUEL COMING OUT. GOT IT SHUT OFF AFTER 30 GALLONS WAS SPILLED.
column169: WE HAVE CHANGED OUR OPERATING PROCEDURES TO ENSURE THAT WHEN THE FILL UNDERGROUND TANKS WE HAVE A POSITIVE AND SEALED CONNECTION BETWEEN THE HOSE AND THE TANK. WITH THIS, FUEL CANNOT GET OUTSIDE OF THE TANK WHEN OVERFILL PROTECTION VALVE SHUTS ON TANK.

column168: THE DELIVERY OPERATOR WAS FILLING THE PREMIUM TANK AND HAD ALMOST COMPLETED THE DELIVERY WHEN IT WAS APPARENT THAT THE FUEL HAD STOPPED FLOWING FROM THE TRUCK INTO THE TANK. HE MADE AND ATTEMPT TO REMOVE THE HOSE FROM THE FILL PORT TO RELEASE THE PRESSURE AND CONTINUE INTO THE U.S.T. AT THAT TIME THE FUEL ROSE QUICKLY FROM THE FILL PORT AND OUT ONTO THE LOT OF THE PROPERTY. THE DELIVERY OPERATOR PRIOR TO REMOVING THE HOSE PLACED OIL DRY AND BOOMS IN FRONT OF A SEWAGE DRAIN TO MINIMIZE THE CONTAMINATION.
column169: THE COMPANY DISCOVERED THAT THE VENT PIPE HAD FROZEN WATER IN ONE OF THEM WHICH PREVENTED THE FUEL FROM BEING ABLE TO ENTER THE TANK. IT WAS THE SERVICE COMPANY WHOM REPLACED THE VENT PIPE THAT INSTRUCTED THE FIRST DRIVER TO USE VAPOR RECOVERY ON HIS TRUCK TO HELP PREVENT AN OCCURRENCE IN THE FUTURE.

column168: ON JANUARY 21ST, 2017 AT 0430 HRS MST IRON HORSE RESPONSE (IHR) WAS DISPATCHED BY DUSTIN RITTER OF CP RAIL (CP) TO CP’S ALYTH YARD. THERE WERE REPORTS OF AN AMMONIA SMELL AND A RELEASE WAS EXPECTED TO BE COMING FROM TRAIN N12 CONTAINING SEVERAL RESIDUE CARS OF UN1005 ANHYDROUS AMMONIA. THE TOTAL CAPACITY OF EACH CAR WAS 129,575 LITERS AND THE EXACT AMOUNT RELEASED IS UNKNOWN. IHR RESPONDED WITH 4 MEMBERS AND TR722 HAZMAT TRAILER. UPON ARRIVAL, CP’S DIESEL LOCOMOTIVE SHOP HAD BEEN EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTION. CALGARY FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SCENE WITH ONE HAZMAT RIG AND ONE ENGINE, ERAP NUMBER WAS CALLED TO NOTIFY PRE ASSESSMENT AND NOTED THAT ERAP NUMBER WAS NOT VALID. CP DGO CONTACTED CANUTEC TO ADVISE AND REQUEST MSDS. A SAFETY BRIEFING WAS HELD AND A PLAN WAS MADE TO IDENTIFY THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE. D RITTER AND B. EDLUND WOULD MAKE ENTRY IN BUNKER GEAR AND SCBA WITH CFD’S HAZMAT TEAM USING AIR MONITORING EQUIPMENT TO DETERMINE WHICH TANK CAR WAS LEAKING. M. THEVENOT AND C. FOSTER WERE STAGED UPWIND IN THE COLD ZONE AS A RAPID INTERVENTION TEAM IF NECESSARY. THE FIRST CAR THAT WAS SIZED UP WAS TILX500966 AND A READING OF 25 PPM WAS DOCUMENTED ON THE GROUND. MONITORING EQUIPMENT REVEALED THE PRESENCE OF AMMONIA ORIGINATING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AT 100 PPM. THE HOUSING WAS OPENED AND IT WAS FOUND WITH LOOSE PLUGS ON THE LIQUID AND VAPOUR VALVES AND BOTH VALVES WERE GIVEN AN EIGHTH OF A TURN TO TIGHTEN. AFTER MONITORING THE HOUSING FOR SEVERAL MINUTES THE LEVELS DROPPED TO 40 PPM. TEAMS MOVED TO THE NEXT CAR (TILX500797) AND A READING OF 500PPM WAS FOUND ON THE GROUND. AFTER CLIMBING THE TANK CAR MONITORING EQUIPMENT ALSO REVEALED THE PRESENCE OF AMMONIA COMING FROM THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. THIS TIME THE LEVELS WERE “OVER RANGE”.
column169: THE HOUSING WAS OPENED AND IT WAS ALSO FOUND WITH LOOSE PLUGS ON THE LIQUID AND VAPOUR VALVES. THE VAPOUR VALVE WAS GIVEN A HALF TURN TO TIGHTEN AND IS BELIEVED TO BE THE LARGEST CAUSE OF THE RELEASE. MONITORING ON TILX500797 CONTINUED AS TEAMS MOVED TO THE NEXT CAR (TILX500802). A READING OF 20 PPM WAS FOUND ON THE GROUND AND THE TOP OF THE CAR WAS CLEAR OF ANY AMMONIA READINGS WITH ALL FITTINGS AND VALVES FOUND CLOSED AND TIGHT. TILX500797 CONTINUED TO PRODUCE READINGS. AT THAT TIME, LOW AIR ALARMS BEGAN TO GO OFF AND ALL TEAMS PULLED BACK TO THE INCIDENT COMMAND LOCATION FOR NEW BOTTLES AND TO DISCUSS FURTHER ACTIONS. UPON RECEIVING CONTACT BY CUSTOMERS EMERGENCY COORDINATOR WE RECEIVED TECHNICAL ADVICE AND A MSDS. THE EMERGENCY NUMBER IS A COOPERATIVE PLAN HELD BETWEEN ORICA AND CANADIAN FERTILIZER. A SOCKET SET WOULD ALSO BE USED TO TIGHTEN ANY LOOSE FLANGE BOLTS ON THE VALVE PACKING. AFTER RE-ENTERING AND COMPLETING THIS TASK THE AMMONIA LEVELS BEGAN TO DROP AND TEAMS AGAIN LEFT THE HOT ZONE. LEVELS ON THE GROUND ADJACENT TO TILX500797 WERE LOWERED TO 25PPM AND 140 PPM WAS RECORDED AT THE HOUSING. AFTER LEVELS DROPPED FAR ENOUGH CP EMPLOYEES WERE GIVEN PERMISSION TO RE-ENTER THE DIESEL SHOP AND CONTINUE WORKING. AT 7:55 D. RITTER OF CP UPDATED CANUTEC AND ALBERTA DANGEROUS GOODS THAT THE LEAK HAD BEEN MITIGATED. IHR WOULD STAY ON THE SCENE AND MONITOR THE AMMONIA LEVELS UNTIL THEY DROPPED TO 0 PPM.

column168: Our vehicle was parked on the shoulder of the road making a delivery. The driver was out of the vehicle with the hose connected to the fill pipe. The Peter Pan Bus collided with the driver side rear of the vehicle. The bus then veered off to the left and across the road and two lawns before hitting a house. The collision ruptured the tank at the bottom rear corner of the tank. The hole was approximately 2" high by 12" wide. The release lasted for approximately 1.5 hrs. The driver diked the immediate area as best he could. He then attempted to plug the hole with equipment from his spill kit and whatever the first responders could provide. The first responders also collected as many trash barrels from the surrounding homes to contain the oil. When the recovery vehicle arrived we suggested picking up the rear of the truck to slow down the release of product which it did.

column168: THE INVESTIGATION INTO THE ACCIDENT REMAINS ONGOING. HOWEVER, BASED OFF OF KNOWN INFORMATION, THE DRIVER HAD BEGUN HIS TRANSFER FROM U.S. ROUTE 33 ONTO I-270 NB WHILE LOADED WITH APPROXIMATELY 8,000 GALLONS OF GASOLINE THAT HE HAD RECENTLY LOADED ONTO THE TRAILER UNIT. THE KNOWN CONDITIONS OF THE ROAD WERE CONSISTENT WITH A RECENT LIGHT RAINFALL; THE ROADWAY WAS WET AND THE SKY WAS OVERCAST. BASED ON LOCAL NEWS REPORTING, THE SPEED LIMIT FOR THE ON-RAMP WAS POSTED 55 MILES-PER-HOUR WITH AN ADVISORY SIGN FOR 40 MILES-PER-HOUR.    AT SOME POINT BEFORE THE APEX OF THE CURVED ROADWAY, THE UNIT APPEARS (AT THIS TIME) TO HAVE STRUCK THE GUARD RAILS ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROADWAY BEFORE RE-ENTERING AND ROLLING OVER ONTO IT’S RIGHT SIDE. UNKNOWN AT THIS TIME WAS WHEN THE GASOLINE IN THE TRAILER WAS IGNITED, CAUSING A SUBSEQUENT FIRE DESTROYING MUCH OF THE TRAILER AND BURNING THE TRACTOR AND THE TOP OF THE RAMP, AND KILLING THE DRIVER. LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDENTS WERE QUICKLY ABLE TO MAKE IT TO THE SCENE, BUT WERE NOT ABLE TO IMMEDIATELY EXTINGUISH THE FIRE. PRODUCT WAS ABLE TO ESCAPE DOWN THE RAMP AND INTO NEARBY GRASSLAND, ENTERING INTO A NEARBY DITCH.     IMMEDIATE REMEDIATION EFFORTS AND EMERGENCY RECONSTRUCTION OF THE ROADWAY WERE COMPLETED AROUND 8:00 PM ON 1/23
column169: LYKINS TRANSPORTATION, INC. REVIEWS ALL INCIDENTS TO DETERMINE WHETHER OR NOT SUCH INCIDENTS COULD HAVE BEEN AVOIDED OR OTHERWISE PREVENTED. IN THIS INSTANCE, LYKINS TRANSPORTATION, INC. HAS NOT YET CONCLUDED THE EXACT CAUSE OF THE CRASH, EXCEPT THAT AT SOME POINT THE UNIT STRUCK A GUARD RAIL. IT IS UNKNOWN WHAT ACTIONS THE DRIVER TOOK TO GET INTO THAT SITUATION, AS WELL AS WHAT ACTIONS HE MAY HAVE TAKEN TO TRY AND CORRECT THE UNIT. THE INVESTIGATION REMAINS ONGOING BY THE DUBLIN POLICE DEPARTMENT.     DURING OUR NEXT QUARTERLY SAFETY MEETING, OUR DRIVERS WILL BE BRIEFED ON THE INCIDENT. THE DRIVERS WILL AGAIN BE ADVISED TO EXERCISE CAUTION WHILE DRIVING ON WET ROADWAYS, ESPECIALLY IN AREAS THAT ARE CURVED, IN ORDER TO GIVE THEMSELVES ENOUGH REACTION TIME TO AVOID ANY OTHER COLLISIONS OR OTHER CHANGES IN CIRCUMSTANCES WHILE DRIVING ON THE ROADWAYS.

column168: FUEL TANKER DRIVER ARRIVED AT CUSTOMER LOCATION TO DELIVER 7,503 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL INTO CUSTOMER’S 10,000 GALLON CAPACITY STORAGE TANK. TANK WAS READING 33” OF FUEL, BUT DRIVER USED A 120” DIAMETER, 10,000 GAL CAPACITY TANK CHART TO DETERMINE THE QUANTITY OF FUEL IN THE TANK, SO HE COULD VERIFY THAT THE 7,503 GALLON LOAD WOULD FIT. 33” IN A 120 DIAMETER, 10K TANK IS 2,232 GALLONS. 7,503 + 2,232 <10,000. SO DRIVER CONFIRMED LOAD WOULD FIT.   ERROR #1: DRIVER USED WRONG TANK CHART. TANK IS A 96” DIAMETER 10K TANK 33” IS 3,090 GALLONS IN A 96”, 10K TANK. 7,503 + 3,090 > 10,000 THUS A SPILL/OVER FILL OCCURRED.  ERROR #2: DRIVER WAS NOT WITHIN 20 FT OF SHUT OFF VALVES. THUS, THE OVERFILL QUANTITY WAS LARGER THAN IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN.
column169: USED THIS AS AN EXAMPLE TO ALL DRIVERS OF THE IMPORTANCE OF STAYING WITHIN 20 FT OF SHUT OFF VALVES + PAYING ATTENTION TO THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  ALSO, RECOMMENDED TO CUSTOMER THAT OVERFILL PROTECTION BE INSTALLED ON THEIR STORAGE TANK. WE AGREED TO SHARE IN THE COST AS IN INCENTIVE FOR THEM TO FOLLOW THROUGH ON THAT.

column168: THIS RELEASE WAS DO TO A ROAD ACCIDENT CAUSED BY DRIVER ERROR (DISTRACTED DRIVING). THIS WAS A TRANSPORTATION UNIT CONSISTING OF A TRACTOR, A 48” LEAD CARGO TRAILER AND A 28” REAR CARGO TANK TRAILER, ALSO KNOWN AS AN A-TRAIN. THE DRIVER TOOK HIS EYES OFF THE ROADWAY FOR A SECOND AND HIS STEER TIRE PULLED THE TRUCK INTO THE SNOW BANK. THE DRIVER INCORRECTLY REACTED BY TRYING TO BRING THE TRUCK BACK INTO THE ROADWAY WHICH CAUSED A WHIPPING MOTION ON THE REAR CARGO TANK TRAILER AND ROLLED ON ITS SIDE WHEN IT CAME BACK ONTO THE ROADWAY PAVEMENT. THE SPILL WAS 27 TO 30 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL AND WAS CONTAINED ON THE PAVED ROADWAY AND THEN COMPLETELY REMOVED AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF. ESTIMATED LOSS, 0 TO .50 GALLONS. THE TRAILER MECHANICALLY SAFE TO OPERATE BACK TO VALDEZ WHERE IT WAS RETURNED.     PLEASE SEE ATTACHMENT #1: ALASKA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION “SITREP REPORT” WHICH WAS SENT TO THE FOLLOWING FEDERAL & STATE AGENCIES:    1. UNITED STATES DEPT. OF THE INTERIOR.  2. NATIONAL MARINE FISHERIES SERVICES.  3. UNITED STATES FISH & WILDLIFE.  4. UNITED STATES COAST GUARD (VALDEZ, AK).  5. UNITED STATES ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY.  6. GOVERNORS OFFICE (ALASKA), STATE EMERGENCY OPERATIONS CENTER, ALASKA DOT AND PUBLIC FACILITIES, ALASKA DEPT. OF FISH & GAME.
column169: THE ONLY ISSUE HERE WAS THE DRIVER WHO HAD WELL OVER 30 YEARS EXPERIENCE OPERATING COMMERCIAL MOTOR VEHICLES. DRIVER HAD ATTENDED SEVERAL MEETINGS WHERE WE TALKED ABOUT DISTRACTED DRIVING. THIS DRIVERS EMPLOYMENT WAS TERMINATED 01/23/2017. WE WILL CONTINUE TO HAVE SAFETY MEETINGS WHERE WE DISCUSS DISTRACTED DRIVING. WE ALSO HAVE AUTOMATIC EVENT RECORDERS IN THE TRUCK CABS AND WE RANDOMLY SELECT A PERCENTAGE OF DRIVERS AND CHECK THERE DRIVING HABITS.   PERSON RESPONSIBLE FOR COMPANY WIDE ACCIDENTS, SPILLS, CLEANUPS, AND REPORTING AT THE TIME OF THIS SPILL WAS OUR FORMER GENERAL MANAGER, BRAIN EVANS. HE WAS RELEASED OF HIS DUTIES ON 07/14/2017 AND IS NO LONGER WITH BIG STATE LOGISTICS.  WE ARE ASSUMING THE REASON HE DID NOT REPORT THIS ON THE DOT F5800 IS BECAUSE THE ACTUAL LOSS AFTER RECOVERY WAS ONLY .05 GALLONS (1/2 GALLON) OR LESS. PLEASE SEE THE ATTACHED EMAIL COPIES AND YOU WILL SEE HOW THE 27 TO 30 GALLON SPILL WAS DETERMINED AND THE ACCOUNTING OF ALL BUT .05 GALLONS WAS RECOVERED. THIS WAS A MISINTERPRETATION OF THE REGULATIONS. MR. EVANS REPLACEMENT HAS BEEN INFORMED OF THIS REGULATION.  ATTACHMENT #2 ARE EMAILS CONCERNING THE LOSS AND RECOVERY.

column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING ON NARROW BLACKTOP ROAD IN 2010 FREIGHT LINER BOBTAIL WHEN HE GLANCED AWAY FROM THE ROAD BRIEFLY. TRUCK WENT ONTO MIDDLE SHOULDER OF ROAD, INTO THE DITCH, AND THEN OVERTURNED ONTO ITS SIDE. DRIVER COULDN’T GET TRUCK ENGINE TO SHUT DOWN AND EVENTUALLY IGNITED EITHER FUEL OR PROPANE & FIRE ENSUED. DRIVER WAS ABLE TO GET AWAY FROM TRUCK TO SAFETY.  EVENTUALLY PRESSURE INCREASED IN CARGO TANK UNTIL REAR HEAD SHELL SPLIT OPEN RELEASING LARGE QUANTITY OF PROPANE. PROPANE IN TANK CONTINUED TO POUR FOR APPROXIMATELY 3 HOURS. INITIAL ACTIONS TO MITIGATE INCIDENT WERE TO EVACUATE FROM HOUSE APPROXIMATELY ½ MILE AWAY.
column169: DRIVER WAS REMINDED OF IMPORTANCE OF ALWAYS KEEPING YOUR EYES ON THE ROAD AHEAD.

column168: DRIVER WAS PUMPING PRODUCT OFF OF TRAILER WITH A PTO PUMP WHICH IS LOCATED ON THE TRUCK. THE PUMP HAS A “T” PIPE, WITH ONE SIDE WHICH HAD THE HOSE CONNECTED TO THE ABOVE GROUND TANK AND THE OTHER SIDE HAD A CAP CLOSURE WITH A VELCRO STRAP TO SECURE. THE STRAP SEEMS TO HAVE CAME LOOSE DUE TO THE AGE OF THE STRAP. THE VIBRATION OF THE PUMP CAUSED THE CLOSURE CAN ON THE CAP TO OPEN UP WHICH THEN CAUSED THE CAP TO FALL OFF AND FUEL TO SPILL TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND. THE PUMP WAS IMMEDIATELY TURNED OFF.
column169: TO PREVENT THE RECURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT WE NO LONGER USE VELCRO STRAPS TO SECURE THE CAP AND CANS. WE ARE NOW USING METAL CLIPS TO SECURE THE CANS ON THE STRAPS.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO LOAD HIS TRUCK FROM OUR OWN LOADING RACK LOCATED IN OUR YARD. HE ENTERED THE NUMBER OF GALLONS OF DYED CARB DIESEL IN THE METER AND PROCEEDED TO LOAD. HE PROCEEDED TO TURN THE PUMP ON TO LOAD PRODUCT AND AS IT WAS LOADING THE COMPARTMENT OVERFILLED CAUSING THE COMPARTMENT ON HIS TRUCK TO OVERFILL. THE OVERFILL PROTECTION SYSTEM FAILED BECAUSE THE SCULLY SYSTEM WASN’T WORKING PROPERLY. IN FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS REVEALED THAT THE METER ON THE LOADING RACK HAD JUST BEEN REPLACED AND THAT THE MAINTENANCE DEPARTMENT FAILED TO PUT THE STICKER THAT THE METER NOW READS IN GALLONS, NOT TENTHS, AND THAT IS WHY THE TRUCK COMPARTMENT WAS OVERFILLED.
column169: BECAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT THE RACK WAS SHUTDOWN, THE SCULLY SYSTEM WAS REPAIRED, AND THE METERS WERE ALL CHECKED AND LABELED PROPERLY. ALSO ALL DRIVERS WERE INFORMED AND TRAINED OF THE NEW RACK CHANGES TO PREVENT THIS INCIDENT FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE.

column168: THE RELEASE OCCURRED WHEN A TANKER TRUCK WENT OFF THE WEST SIDE OF THE SOUTHBOUND LANE OF JUDD ROAD TO AVOID A DEER IN THE ROAD. THE TRUCK STRUCK ONE OR MORE TREES RESULTING IN A RUPTURE OF THE TANK ON RIGHT FRONT CORNER AND THE SUBSEQUENT LOSS OF AN ESTIMATED 1,750 GALLONS OF #2 HEATING OIL. THERE WERE NO INJURIES. THE RELEASED FUEL OIL FLOWED ONTO THE GROUND ADJACENT TO JUDD ROAD AND IMPACTED SOIL AND GROUND WATER. THE CT DEEP SPILL NUMBER ASSIGNED TO THE RELEASE IS 2017-00478.APPROXIMATELY 1,093 TONS OF IMPACTED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED AND REMOVED OFFSITE. POST-EXCAVATION SOIL SAMPLES INDICATED RESIDUAL CONCENTRATIONS WERE REDUCED TO BELOW CONNECTICUT DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY &ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION (CTDEEP) REMEDIATION STANDARD REGULATION GA POLLUTANT MOBILITY CRITERIA AND RESIDENTIAL DIRECT EXPOSURE CRITERIA. VACUUM TRUCKS REMOVED APPROXIMATELY 133,979 GALLONS OF OIL AND GROUNDWATER FROM THE EXCAVATION AND RECOVERY WELLS BETWEEN FEBRUARY 2 AND FEBRUARY 10, 2017.SURROUNDING POTABLE WELLS HAVE BEEN SAMPLED ON FOUR OCCASIONS WITHOUT DETECTION OF TARGET ANALYTES. CTDEEP AND LOCAL HEALTH OFFICIALS HAVE BEEN COPIED ON ALL REPORTS.

column168: Train crew reported car leaking from top and an odor of alcohol around car. Car was placed on Spill Pan and inspected by Mechanical forces.  No evidence of liquid or vapor leak.  A NS approved Environmental Contractor was called to check the car.  Investigation with 4 gas meter revealed a vapor leak around the hinge area of the manway.  Manway was opened and the hard style gasket was found to be deteriorated.  Gasket was replaced with a "nozzle" style soft gasket and manway re-secured.  Manway area was checked with meter an no readings were detected.  Car was released back into transportation.
